about Levina Teerlinc.

00:05:50.810 --> 00:05:56.400
Pantrix [phonetic] is
the feminine of painter.

00:05:56.400 --> 00:05:59.400
Levina Teerlinc was a rarity.

00:05:59.400 --> 00:06:01.900
She was a successful
woman artist [inaudible].

00:06:01.900 --> 00:06:09.380 position:56%
She served all four Tudor
monarchs, in particular Elizabeth I.

00:06:09.380 --> 00:06:12.630
She was a simple woman
and friend to Elizabeth,

00:06:12.630 --> 00:06:16.930
and she painted miniature
portraits of the queen.

00:06:16.930 --> 00:06:21.660
Teerlinc was born 1510
to 1520 in Flanders,

00:06:21.660 --> 00:06:24.400
the eldest of Simon
Bening's five daughters,

00:06:24.400 --> 00:06:29.030
and the only one known
to work as an artist.

00:06:29.030 --> 00:06:32.440
Her heritage as illuminator,
miniaturist, scribner [phonetic]

00:06:32.440 --> 00:06:37.170
and calligrapher can be traced
to her father and grandfather.

00:06:37.170 --> 00:06:41.620
Simon and Sanders Bening,
masters of a specialized art form,

00:06:41.620 --> 00:06:44.870
the illuminated manuscript.

00:06:44.870 --> 00:06:50.270
They worked with other noted
painters on the Grimani Breviary,

00:06:50.270 --> 00:06:54.070
circa 1510, which is
a book of prayers.

00:06:54.070 --> 00:06:57.870
The Grimani Breviary has 1670 pages

00:06:57.870 --> 00:07:01.690
of which 120 are full
page miniatures.

00:07:01.690 --> 00:07:06.400
It represents the height of Flemish
manuscripts within the nation.

00:07:07.630 --> 00:07:09.360
The Marfond [phonetic] Library

00:07:09.360 --> 00:07:13.760
at Yale University holds a
facsimile copy of the Breviary,

00:07:13.760 --> 00:07:17.810
and one of their curators
said, "the borders of this page

00:07:17.810 --> 00:07:20.830
and many others throughout
the Breviary are filled

00:07:20.830 --> 00:07:25.290
with exquisite [inaudible]
depictions of natural forms.

00:07:25.290 --> 00:07:29.960
The [inaudible] elements are a
hallmark of the Bening studio."

00:07:29.960 --> 00:07:34.390
It was famous for these
vary naturalistic borders.

00:07:34.390 --> 00:07:36.650
Miniatures developed
from the tradition

00:07:36.650 --> 00:07:39.320
of religious manuscript
illumination.

00:07:39.320 --> 00:07:42.030
The miniatures in the
Grimani Breviary are part

00:07:42.030 --> 00:07:44.170
of an enormous book,

00:07:44.170 --> 00:07:47.280
while Teerlinc's miniatures
were usually painted

00:07:47.280 --> 00:07:50.840
in vellum glued to playing cards.

00:07:50.840 --> 00:07:56.370
They could be as small as a
little over 1-1/2 inches by less

00:07:56.370 --> 00:08:01.240
than 1-1/4 inches, to the works
I will show you are engaged,

00:08:01.240 --> 00:08:04.230
excuse me, enlarged many times.

00:08:04.230 --> 00:08:08.030
Working on a tiny surface,
Teerlinc created realistic images

00:08:08.030 --> 00:08:11.940
of Elizabeth and other
figures in the court.

00:08:11.940 --> 00:08:16.370
An accident at birth sent
Teerlinc on her career path.

00:08:16.370 --> 00:08:20.520
She had no brother to take
over her father's studio,

00:08:20.520 --> 00:08:22.790
so Simon taught her his art.

00:08:22.790 --> 00:08:27.050
His studio produced
magnificent one of a kind books,

00:08:27.050 --> 00:08:32.830
but as Susan James says in the
feminine dynamic in English art,

00:08:32.830 --> 00:08:37.820
"Simon Bening took Flemish
illumination to its final zenith.

00:08:37.820 --> 00:08:43.100
It was an art form which became
obsolete upon his death."

00:08:43.100 --> 00:08:47.480
Illuminated manuscripts were in
decline because of the invention

00:08:47.480 --> 00:08:51.010
of the printing press
and movable type,

00:08:51.010 --> 00:08:54.290
but Teerlinc's skills
were transferable.

00:08:54.290 --> 00:08:58.680
She used them to forge a
career in service to Royalty.

00:09:02.190 --> 00:09:06.390
By the late 1530s, she had
finished her apprenticeship

00:09:06.390 --> 00:09:10.460
and became a fully fledged
member of her father's workshop.

00:09:10.460 --> 00:09:15.060
She was admitted to the Rogue
Painters Guild, which was required

00:09:15.060 --> 00:09:17.280
for her career as a miniaturist.

00:09:17.280 --> 00:09:19.400
She married George Teerlinc,

00:09:19.400 --> 00:09:26.030
the son of a prosperous gentry
family between 1540 and 1542.

00:09:26.030 --> 00:09:31.580
The couple moved to England in
1546 when Catherine Parr, the sixth

00:09:31.580 --> 00:09:35.640
and last queen of Henry
VIII, hired Teerlinc

00:09:35.640 --> 00:09:39.710
as court painter after
Hans Holbein died.

00:09:39.710 --> 00:09:42.410
The Teerlincs were
invited to live in London

00:09:42.410 --> 00:09:47.810
because Catherine Parr had learned
of Levina's skills as an artist.

00:09:47.810 --> 00:09:51.860
George Teerlinc's career
was secondary to his wife's.

00:09:51.860 --> 00:09:56.600 position:56%
He promoted himself as an aristocrat
and became a gentleman pensioner,

00:09:56.600 --> 00:10:03.410
the male equivalent
of a maid of honor.

00:10:03.410 --> 00:10:04.980
This helped advance both his

00:10:04.980 --> 00:10:08.890
and his wife's position
at the English court.

00:10:08.890 --> 00:10:13.400
Susan Frye, author of Pens and
Needles, Women's Textualities

00:10:13.400 --> 00:10:18.360
in Early Modern England, says,
"George may have been a dealer

00:10:18.360 --> 00:10:22.960
in tapestries, textiles and
artwork produced in the Netherlands

00:10:22.960 --> 00:10:27.650
and it's likely that he acted
as an agent for his wife.

00:10:27.650 --> 00:10:31.990 position:56%
Levina Teerlinc probably spent the
period immediately after her arrival

00:10:31.990 --> 00:10:35.850
in England working for Queen
Catherine and her sister,

00:10:35.850 --> 00:10:39.940
Ann Parr, a prominent art patron.

00:10:39.940 --> 00:10:46.350
After Henry VIII died, Teerlinc
worked for Edward VI and Mary I,

00:10:46.350 --> 00:10:51.100
and when Elizabeth became queen
in 1558, Teerlinc was retained

00:10:51.100 --> 00:10:55.670
as a miniaturist for
the rest of her life.

00:10:55.670 --> 00:10:58.110
As court painter to Elizabeth,

00:10:58.110 --> 00:11:01.870
she was paid the salary
of 40 pounds a year.

00:11:01.870 --> 00:11:06.630
In addition, she received 20 pounds
a year directly from Elizabeth.

00:11:06.630 --> 00:11:10.910 position:56%
This was twice what Hans Holbein had
received and more than the salary

00:11:10.910 --> 00:11:13.780
of Nicholas Hilliard, a
celebrated court painter,

00:11:13.780 --> 00:11:17.650
who is better known
today than Teerlinc.

00:11:17.650 --> 00:11:23.120
Hilliard's salary did not reach
40 pounds a year until 1599.

00:11:23.120 --> 00:11:24.440
Another woman artist,

00:11:24.440 --> 00:11:28.190
Susanna Horenbout paved
the way for Teerlinc.

00:11:28.190 --> 00:11:36.010 position:56%
She was from the Netherlands and was
active from the 1520s to the 1540s.

00:11:36.010 --> 00:11:38.890
She was trained by her father,
the artist Gerard Horenbout,

00:11:38.890 --> 00:11:42.050
and her brother, Lucas, was
a well-known miniaturist.

00:11:42.050 --> 00:11:45.990
Henry VIII brought the
Horenbout family to England

00:11:45.990 --> 00:11:50.460
to paint portrait miniatures
and illuminated manuscripts.

00:11:50.460 --> 00:11:54.790
Horenbout may have
lived into the 1550s.

00:11:54.790 --> 00:11:58.250
By 1554 or earlier, she had died.

00:11:58.250 --> 00:12:02.060 position:56%
Now I'll talk about Teerlinc's work.

00:12:02.060 --> 00:12:07.400
Teerlinc worked for Edward
VI, Henry VIII's son.

00:12:07.400 --> 00:12:12.480
In summer of 1547 at the beginning
of Edward's reign, Teerlinc appears

00:12:12.480 --> 00:12:15.190
on the list of the King's artists.

00:12:15.190 --> 00:12:18.410
Her appearance on this list
was a unique achievement

00:12:18.410 --> 00:12:22.650
for a 16th century woman, and
it's even more significant

00:12:22.650 --> 00:12:25.290
because she is listed first.

00:12:25.290 --> 00:12:30.350
The record shows that in 1552,
Teerlinc presented a group

00:12:30.350 --> 00:12:34.460
of miniatures to the King
as a New Year's gift.

00:12:34.460 --> 00:12:37.860
When Mary came to the
thrown in 1553,

00:12:37.860 --> 00:12:41.180
Teerlinc was retained
as court painter.

00:12:41.180 --> 00:12:47.450 position:56%
The earliest surviving examples of
Teerlinc's art is a portrait of Mary

00:12:47.450 --> 00:12:54.240
on the Coram Rege Roll
of October 1553.

00:12:54.240 --> 00:12:59.600
Coram Rege Rolls were records of
the proceedings of the King's bench

00:12:59.600 --> 00:13:04.890
where the text of the roll always
began with a capital P for pasita,

00:13:04.890 --> 00:13:07.320
which is a public port or assembly.

00:13:07.320 --> 00:13:10.290
Mary's portrait was
painted within the P,

00:13:10.290 --> 00:13:13.710
but you can't see the whole P,
but you can see Mary's portrait.

00:13:13.710 --> 00:13:17.820
The P is surrounding the
portrait, but I can't,

00:13:17.820 --> 00:13:24.240
I'm not able to show you the
whole letter P. Also for Mary,

00:13:24.240 --> 00:13:29.040
Teerlinc made an illuminated
manuscript, Queen Mary's manual

00:13:29.040 --> 00:13:33.280
for blessing cramp rings
and touching for the evil,

00:13:33.280 --> 00:13:36.490
the rituals of the royal
healing ceremonies.

00:13:36.490 --> 00:13:43.430
This is circa 1553 to 1558, so
it could have been about in any

00:13:43.430 --> 00:13:46.070
of the five years of Mary's reign.

00:13:46.070 --> 00:13:50.760
Cramp rings were given to women to
ward off the pain of menstruation

00:13:50.760 --> 00:13:56.050
and childbirth, and I don't
know what they looked like.

00:13:57.270 --> 00:14:00.560
[laughter] So that's
the description.

00:14:00.560 --> 00:14:02.870
And here is the manuscript.

00:14:02.870 --> 00:14:06.280
Touching for the evil refers
to the ritual of the king

00:14:06.280 --> 00:14:10.520
or queen touching a person
suffering from scropula [phonetic],

00:14:10.520 --> 00:14:12.720 position:56%
and inflammation of the lymph glands

00:14:12.720 --> 00:14:16.050
that can cause hearing
loss and blindness.

00:14:16.050 --> 00:14:20.240
The recto [phonetic] is titled, the
Ceremony for the Healing of Them

00:14:20.240 --> 00:14:23.010
that be Diseased with
the King's Evil.

00:14:23.010 --> 00:14:26.980
The borso [phonetic] shows
Mary applying the royal touch.

00:14:26.980 --> 00:14:28.750
And there she is.

00:14:28.750 --> 00:14:31.070
There's a little boy,
a little [inaudible],

00:14:31.070 --> 00:14:35.590
and she's applying
the touch [inaudible].

00:14:35.590 --> 00:14:40.910
When Elizabeth became queen in
1558, Teerlinc became a gentlewoman

00:14:40.910 --> 00:14:43.360
and friend to the monarch.

00:14:44.500 --> 00:14:48.120
She was talented at
making her way in court.

00:14:48.120 --> 00:14:52.040
Susan James says although
technically a royal servant,

00:14:52.040 --> 00:14:55.440
Teerlinc appears to have been
accepted at the English court

00:14:55.440 --> 00:14:57.960
as an honorary aristocrat.

00:14:57.960 --> 00:15:02.200
She had known Elizabeth since
the latter was 11 years old.

00:15:02.200 --> 00:15:04.980
Because of her presence
in the royal chamber,

00:15:04.980 --> 00:15:08.230
Teerlinc had significant
influence with the queen.

00:15:09.290 --> 00:15:12.340
In Elizabeth's court, New
Year's Day was an occasion

00:15:12.340 --> 00:15:15.130
for giving lavish gifts.

00:15:15.130 --> 00:15:21.960
From 1558 to 1576, Teerlinc
painted miniatures that she gave

00:15:21.960 --> 00:15:24.840
to the queen as New Year's gifts.

00:15:24.840 --> 00:15:29.680
This is a partial list of her
work, and these are extracts

00:15:29.680 --> 00:15:34.510 position:56%
from the official records so you see
the differences in the spellings.

