00:15:56.330 --> 00:15:59.210
And her last name, Terlyng,

00:15:59.210 --> 00:16:02.120
there's another spelling
of Terling, and Taolyng.

00:16:02.120 --> 00:16:06.160
So the spellings are not consistent
at all, the spellings of her name.

00:16:06.160 --> 00:16:11.250
Elizabeth did not like to sit
for portraits, but she is known

00:16:11.250 --> 00:16:17.250
to have sat for five artists,
including Teerlinc in 1551

00:16:17.250 --> 00:16:20.620
and Nicholas Hilliard in 1572.

00:16:20.620 --> 00:16:25.290
Susan James says Teerlinc's
miniatures were intimate private

00:16:25.290 --> 00:16:29.990
gifts, evidence of the close
bond shared by these two women.

00:16:29.990 --> 00:16:32.710
Painted for the queen's eyes only,

00:16:32.710 --> 00:16:34.850
they represent a private
conversation

00:16:34.850 --> 00:16:37.400
between ruler and artist.

00:16:37.400 --> 00:16:39.300
Teerlinc had access to the queen

00:16:39.300 --> 00:16:42.340
that a male painter
would not have had.

00:16:42.340 --> 00:16:45.990
Susan James says that
Teerlinc's work helped Mary

00:16:45.990 --> 00:16:50.780 position:56%
and Elizabeth assert their God-given
right to rule England by ensuring

00:16:50.780 --> 00:16:54.380
that their images were
prominently displayed.

00:16:54.380 --> 00:16:58.400
In addition to miniatures,
portraits, and manuscripts,

00:16:58.400 --> 00:17:02.320
it's likely that Teerlinc created
[inaudible] legal documents

00:17:02.320 --> 00:17:06.270
and designed seals,
coins, and needlework.

00:17:06.270 --> 00:17:08.850
Scholars attribute
