00:17:08.850 --> 00:17:10.870
of Elizabeth I to Teerlinc.

00:17:10.870 --> 00:17:15.100
The designs were executed
by another artist.

00:17:16.610 --> 00:17:22.430
In 1573, a manual entitled A Very
Proper Treatise wherein is breefley

00:17:22.430 --> 00:17:26.830
set forth the art of Limming,
never put in print before his time.

00:17:26.830 --> 00:17:30.290
The title on this one
is a little different

00:17:30.290 --> 00:17:32.790
because it's a different edition,

00:17:32.790 --> 00:17:35.040
but it was published
anonymously in 1573.

00:17:35.040 --> 00:17:38.180
Limming refers to miniature
painting.

00:17:39.860 --> 00:17:43.620
James believes that
Teerlinc wrote the manual,

00:17:43.620 --> 00:17:46.710
thus ensuring that the art of
miniature painting would be passed

00:17:46.710 --> 00:17:49.450
onto a new generation of artist.

00:17:49.450 --> 00:17:54.070
A Very Proper Treatise was a
detailed how to manual intended

00:17:54.070 --> 00:17:58.010
for painters who wanted to
learn the art of miniatures.

00:17:58.010 --> 00:18:00.700
It was useful because
miniatures were very popular

00:18:00.700 --> 00:18:02.840
with Elizabeth in her court.

00:18:02.840 --> 00:18:07.030
The queen exchanged them with other
European rules, women who wore them

00:18:07.030 --> 00:18:09.850
as jewelry, and they
were given and received

00:18:09.850 --> 00:18:12.810
in romantic and courtship rituals.

00:18:12.810 --> 00:18:15.300
To talk about Levina
Teerlinc's work,

00:18:15.300 --> 00:18:19.100
I need to also discuss
Nicholas Hilliard.

00:18:19.100 --> 00:18:23.050
Hilliard lived from 1547 to 1619,

00:18:23.050 --> 00:18:26.550
so he was 30 to 40 years
younger than Teerlinc.

00:18:26.550 --> 00:18:30.280
In about 1570, Hilliard
became a miniature painter

00:18:30.280 --> 00:18:32.040
to Queen Elizabeth.

00:18:32.040 --> 00:18:35.710
Thus, Teerlinc and Hilliard were
painting miniatures during the same

00:18:35.710 --> 00:18:40.230
period since Teerlinc
lived until 1576.

00:18:40.230 --> 00:18:44.660
Roy Strong, a prominent art
historian, and Susan James believed

00:18:44.660 --> 00:18:48.500
that Teerlinc taught
Nicholas Hilliard his art.

00:18:48.500 --> 00:18:53.300
But art historians differ in their
opinions about which Teerlinc

00:18:53.300 --> 00:18:58.280
or Hilliary executed some of
the works and caution is needed.

00:18:59.380 --> 00:19:01.540
Some works originally attributed

00:19:01.540 --> 00:19:05.670
to Hilliard have been more
recently attributed to Teerlinc,

00:19:05.670 --> 00:19:08.600
especially by feminist art critics.

00:19:08.600 --> 00:19:11.990
Teerlinc did not sign her
work, and very few miniatures

00:19:11.990 --> 00:19:16.390
from this period exist, to
attribution is difficult.

00:19:18.010 --> 00:19:21.710
Roy Strong and other critics
have associated Teerlinc

00:19:21.710 --> 00:19:26.710
with an important miniature
known as an Elizabethan Maundy.

00:19:26.710 --> 00:19:31.380
Painted around 1565, it illustrates
the queen washing the feet

00:19:31.380 --> 00:19:35.840
of poor women on Maundy Thursday,
the day before Good Friday.

00:19:35.840 --> 00:19:39.880
However, Susan James believes
Teerlinc did not paint

00:19:39.880 --> 00:19:41.410
this miniature.

00:19:41.410 --> 00:19:48.040
The Lute miniature, circa 1574
to 1576, has been attributed

00:19:48.040 --> 00:19:50.940
to both Hilliard and Teerlinc.

00:19:50.940 --> 00:19:53.500
Strong and other scholars
have associated Teerlinc

00:19:53.500 --> 00:19:57.000
with less sophisticated
miniature portraits of Elizabeth

00:19:57.000 --> 00:19:58.410
as princess and as queen.

00:19:58.410 --> 00:20:01.290 position:56%
And this is Elizabeth as a princess,

00:20:01.290 --> 00:20:05.990
and you can see how
small the diameter is.

00:20:05.990 --> 00:20:09.920
This is thousands of times bigger.

00:20:09.920 --> 00:20:13.610
This is Elizabeth as
queen of England.

00:20:13.610 --> 00:20:18.950
This is a miniature of Lady
Catherine Grey, Elizabeth's cousin

00:20:18.950 --> 00:20:22.350
and a possible successor
to the throne.

00:20:22.350 --> 00:20:25.810
This is Mary Dudley, Lady Sidney.

00:20:25.810 --> 00:20:28.820 position:56%
And this is Lady Hunsdon [phonetic].

00:20:28.820 --> 00:20:31.640
These are some of Teerlinc's
miniatures.

00:20:33.020 --> 00:20:36.990
Strong writes that in these
miniatures and Elizabethan Maundy,

00:20:36.990 --> 00:20:40.240
the figures are not
particularly well drawn.

00:20:40.240 --> 00:20:44.810
They are typically elongated, and
the arms are always very thin.

00:20:44.810 --> 00:20:48.150
You can see them there,
very thin arms.

00:20:48.150 --> 00:20:52.440
He says the draftsman ship is weak
and the painting is thin; however,

00:20:52.440 --> 00:20:55.610
he also says that Teerlinc's
work shows a degree

00:20:55.610 --> 00:20:58.960
of innovation in subject matter.

00:20:58.960 --> 00:21:01.080
Her miniatures may be
lacking in technique,

00:21:01.080 --> 00:21:03.730
but the fact that they were
created by a woman artist

00:21:03.730 --> 00:21:07.090 position:56%
in the Tudor era makes them notable.

00:21:07.090 --> 00:21:09.520
A side-by-side comparison
of Teerlinc's

00:21:09.520 --> 00:21:14.060
and Hilliard's work shows
differences in technique.

00:21:14.060 --> 00:21:19.140 position:56%
The rose is miniature on the right,
is generally attributed to Hilliard.

00:21:19.140 --> 00:21:22.530
The miniature shows
great delicacy of touch,

00:21:22.530 --> 00:21:25.450
and Elizabeth's expression
is serene.

00:21:25.450 --> 00:21:28.870
The miniature of Elizabeth as
queen of England attributed

00:21:28.870 --> 00:21:31.520
to Teerlinc is less refined.

00:21:31.520 --> 00:21:34.510
It shows a more girlish
queen with an expression

00:21:34.510 --> 00:21:38.560
that is not uncheerful
but also a little blank.

00:21:38.560 --> 00:21:41.520
Susan Durand in the
Myth of Elizabeth says

00:21:41.520 --> 00:21:45.530
that in Hilliard's miniature the
white roses in Elizabeth's hair

00:21:45.530 --> 00:21:51.640
and pinned to her dress signify the
chastity of a marriageable maiden.

00:21:51.640 --> 00:21:53.750
The same flowers are
present in portraits

00:21:53.750 --> 00:21:56.370
of other young unmarried women.

00:21:56.370 --> 00:22:00.760
In the queen's black and white
costume, white symbolizes purity,

00:22:00.760 --> 00:22:05.540
simplicity, faithfulness and
joy, all desirable qualities

00:22:05.540 --> 00:22:08.880
in a woman seeking
a marriage partner.

00:22:08.880 --> 00:22:13.260
In this case, black stands for
constancy, not [inaudible].

00:22:13.260 --> 00:22:18.530
During the first eight months of
1572, Elizabeth was negotiating

00:22:18.530 --> 00:22:22.560
for marriage with the French
Duke of Anjou, and it's likely

00:22:22.560 --> 00:22:26.340
that the miniature was
painted with this in mind.

00:22:26.340 --> 00:22:28.010
I've talked about Levina's work.

00:22:28.010 --> 00:22:32.990 position:56%
Let me give you a little more
information on the rest of her life.

00:22:32.990 --> 00:22:41.410
In 1547 or 1548, Levina and George
Teerlinc traveled back to Flanders.

00:22:41.410 --> 00:22:45.400
She was pregnant on their return
to English, and her son, Marcus,

00:22:45.400 --> 00:22:50.040
was born in 1548 or 1549
in Calet [phonetic].

00:22:50.040 --> 00:22:52.980
Calet belonged to English
at the time,

00:22:52.980 --> 00:22:57.040 position:56%
and the Teerlincs wanted their son
to be a subject of the English crown

00:22:57.040 --> 00:22:59.220
so he could inherit
property in English.

00:22:59.220 --> 00:23:06.160
In 1566, her husband leased land
in Stepney, a district of London,

00:23:06.160 --> 00:23:10.590
and built a house for the
large sum of 500 pounds.

00:23:10.590 --> 00:23:16.550
The same year, she and her husband
and son became English citizens.

00:23:16.550 --> 00:23:20.280
Little known today, her
career almost entirely exists

00:23:20.280 --> 00:23:22.410
by her successor Hilliard.

00:23:22.410 --> 00:23:26.700
Teerlinc is nevertheless an example
of a talented women succeeding

00:23:26.700 --> 00:23:29.320
in a field dominated by men.

00:23:29.320 --> 00:23:31.580 position:56%
Look closely, and you will find her.

00:23:31.580 --> 00:23:35.070
First, in her father's
workshop, learning her trade,

00:23:35.070 --> 00:23:40.630
and later painting with a minute
brush on a tiny piece of velum,

00:23:40.630 --> 00:23:44.110
capturing Elizabeth's likeness
for the queen's pleasure

00:23:44.110 --> 00:23:47.500
and for foreign princes
and diplomats.

00:23:47.500 --> 00:23:54.020
Teerlinc died on June 23,
1576, probably in Stepney.

00:23:54.020 --> 00:23:59.460
She was between 56 and 66 years
old at the time of her death.

00:23:59.460 --> 00:24:04.590
She was buried at the St.
Dunstan Parish church in Stepney.

00:24:04.590 --> 00:24:07.750
